 First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval name <i>Nigellus</i>, a Latinized version (ostensibly representing a diminutive of Latin <i>niger</i> ‘black’) of the vernacular <i>Ni(h)el</i>, i.e.   Neil .  Although it is frequently found in medieval records, this form was probably not used in everyday life before its revival by antiquarians such as  Sir Walter  Scott in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":42,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":51,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Nigel de Peyton I was born about 1173, in Boxford, Suffolk, England. He married Maud de Stamundeshey. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1242, in Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, England, at the age of 71."},"et":{"about 1173–about 1242":"umbes 1173–umbes 1242","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1215–1287":"1215–1287","1173–1242":"1173–1242","about 1173":"umbes 1173","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","about 1215":"umbes 1215","1287":"1287","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","1173":"1173","about 1242":"umbes 1242","Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Peyton Hall Suffolk, England":"Boxford, Suffolk, England","Ramsholt, Suffolk, England":"Ramsholt